Part II - (US Flights Delay exploration )¶

by (Yaninthé Tiomene)¶

Investigation Overview¶

In this part of investigation, we will try to answer these questions:

  • What are origins/Destinations with maximum delay / cancelation?
  • Airline with most delay / cancelation?
  • What are the preferred times for flights to occur? Are there any changes over multiple years?

Dataset Overview¶

The dataset that will be used is from Dataverse and it reports flights in the United States, including carriers, arrival and departure delays from 1987 to 2008. But due to my CPU and GPU capacity, I will only consider data for 2006, and 2007. We could have considered flights data of 2008, but it only has records up to April of 2008, as the hole dataset was published in October of 2008. If we want to compare flights per month or per year the result may be biased. It consists of 14595137 entries and 33 features where majorities are numericals.

Distribution of departure and arrival delay¶

Arrival and Departure delays are mostly located on the left side of the graph, with a long tail to the right. The majority of departure delays are short (earlier flights and departure flights delay between -20 and 70 minutes) , and the longest delays, while unusual, are more heavy loaded in time. ArrDelay is nearest to a normal distribution, but skew to the right.

Correlation between Arrival delay and Departure delay¶

ArrDelay and DepDelay are highly correlated with one another. Which is what expected, since a flight which is delayed at departure should normally have a delay at arrival. The higher the delay is at departure, the higher it should be at arrival. We can also see that there are earlier flights in departure (more than 16 hours earlier than scheduled) which are late at arrival (they might be outliers).

Number of flight per class Of delay¶

Most of the flights (58.3%) departed less than 30 minutes earlier as shceduled and 29.2% departed less than 30 minutes later as scheduled. Most of the flights (52.5%) arrived less than 30 minutes earlier as scheduled and 32.6% arrived less than 30 minutes later as scheduled.

Top 10 busiest Airport (origin/Destination)¶

We have same top 10 busiest airport from origin and destination, with ATL being the most busiest one, with more than 800k flights in arrival and same in departure.

Airports (Origin/Destination) which are subject to maximum delays¶

  • As origin, none of the top 10 busiest airport is amongst airports with maximum average delays. PIP is the airport with maximum average delay in departure flight, while ACK is the one in arrival flight with an average delay of more than 40 minutes each.

  • As destination, none of the top 10 busiest airport is amongst airports with maximum average delays. CYS is the airport with maximum average delay in departure, while ACK is the one in arrival with an average delay of around 30 minutes each.

  • Amongst the top 10 busiest airports, ORD, and EWR seem to have more delay with a mean of around 17.5 minutes delay in departure and 16 minutes in arrival. ATL which is the most busiest airport only has a mean delay of around 14 minutes in departure and 13 minutes in arrival. LAX airport is the airport with less average delay (around 7.5 minutes in departure and 6.5 minutes in arrival).

Airports (Origin/Destination) which are mostly subject to cancellation¶

ORD which was the second busiest airport, is the airport with more cancelled flights. All top 10 cancelled flights airport, has more cancelled flight in 2007 than 2006, except DEN airport. ATL which is the busiest flight airport is amongst top 10 cancelled flight airport. December is the month with more cancelled flight at these 10 airports. Saturday is the day with less cancelled flight from almost all these 10 airport.

Airlines which are subject to maximum average delays¶

WN which was the carrier with highest number of flights, does not have larger delay. But means vary a lot, EV and TZ have the highest mean, where AH and AQ have the less mean both for ArrDelay and DepDelay.

Airlines with most cancelled flights¶

Number of cancelled flight per carrier varies a lot. There are more cancelled flight in 2007 than 2006 for all carriers except TZ. MQ is the carrier with more cancelled flights. December and February are months with more cancelled flight for almost all carrier. Saturday seems to be the day with less cancelled flight for almost all carrier.

Flight delay and time (PM/AM)¶

In our dataset there are more flights scheduled in the evening(PM) than morning(AM). It also appears that, there are more earlier flights departure and arrival (less than 30 minutes earlier) than any other flight delay category both in the morning and in the evening. We can also see that there are more earlier flight departure (less than 30 minutes earlier) than earlier flight arrival. Late flight departure and arrival (less than 30 minutes delay and less than 5hours delays) are prety same both in the morning and in the evening.

Delays across month and year are prety the same. Same for days of the week. But Saturday and Sunday have the smallest average delay for evening flight and morning flight respectively. There are more and higher delays for flights scheduled in the evening(PM).

Cancelled flight and time (PM/AM)¶

Flights scheduled in the evening (PM) are mostly subject to cancellation.
